\begin_layout Standard
In studying the issue of separated social reference groups, we have adopted
 an approach slightly different from the studies in conspicuous consumption.
 Instead of focusing on visible consumption, we view status consumption
 as a combination of expensive durable goods and high-quality non-durable
 consumption.
 We then compare the combined effect of the two on consumers that are spread
 across different age-groups and levels of urbanisation.
 Using an intertemporal substitution framework with life-cycle effects,
 we attempt to endogenise the role of personal characteristics (such as
 social class, level of education) which may influence status directly or
 through access to long-term durable goods (which in turn influence status).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model for status competition with owned long-term goods and consumption
 of quality is based on a social-deference view of status that has been
 embraced in many economic studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy,corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The key argument is that if the role of status consumption is to influence
 a ranking of income and/or wealth, it follows that the status for two consumers
 with same personal characteristics and a fixed set of needs can only compete
 with either quality in non-durable consumption or ownership of long-term
 durable goods.
\end_layout

