\begin_layout Standard
The detailed market prices are seldom available in a typical consumption
 survey - and issue that is often circumvented by focusing on visible consumptio
n - a particular instance of status consumption that is meant to be futile
 for except for signaling purposes.
 The futility of status goods also ensures the separability of demand for
 visible goods - while viewing a narrowed context of quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We argue that the futility assumption cannot be made in severely unequal
 societies where wealth differences may be far too wide to be narrowed with
 visible (or high quality) non-durable consumption.
 As status consumption comprises both of quality across commodities and
 ownership of durable goods, the contribution of durable goods to the ranking
 order might dominate any changes with visible (high quality) non-durable
 consumption.
 Evaluating the above framework in the particular case of Tanzania, we discuss
 how quality in non-durable consumption could be segregated by long-term
 characteristics (e.g.
 such as education of parents) and availability of certain durable goods.
\end_layout

